article.description: Mwadi Mabika had 20 points and eight assists and DeLisha Milton scored 17 points as the Sparks rolled to a 71-63 victory over the New York Liberty in Game 1 of the WNBA Finals on Thursday night.
article.headline: Sparks win opener, need one more to repeat

images.name: Leslie_Lisa 020829 inline
images.caption: Lisa Leslie, who had 15 points, nine rebounds and three blocks, looks for a hole in the Liberty's defense.

article.linkText: Sparks just one win away from back-to-back titles
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- When the Los Angeles Sparks needed a second-half lift, they turned to their three most reliable players.
Thursday, Aug. 29
New York came out and was fantastic in the first half, doing all the right things and hitting seven of its first eight 3-point attempts. The energy level was high and the crowd was phenomenal.

But as the game progressed, the Liberty seemed to forget about their inside game. Tamika Whitmore and Tari Phillips dominated the paint in New York's first two playoff series, but at halftime on Thursday, Whitmore had scored just one point and Phillips seven. They ended up combining for 17, but that's barely half as many as they had been averaging in the playoffs.

All along, we said this series would be won on the boards, and Los Angeles won the battle Thursday. The Sparks, who had 13 offensive boards, outrebounded the Liberty 37-25. To stop a team such as L.A. that likes to run, you have to rebound and limit its possessions.

Regardless of what happens in Games 2 or 3, the Liberty deserve a lot of credit. New York came out with a lot of heart and desire, played its tail off and looked great with no signs of the fatigue we might have expected.

Mwadi Mabika was outstanding for Los Angeles. She could do anything she wanted off the dribble.
Mwadi Mabika, Lisa Leslie and DeLisha Milton did not let their teammates down, and the Sparks are one win from their second straight WNBA championship. Mabika scored 20 points, Milton added 17 and Leslie had 15 to lead the Sparks to a 71-63 victory over the New York Liberty on Thursday night in Game 1 of the WNBA Finals. Game 2 in the best-of-three series is Saturday in Los Angeles. The Liberty are 0-3 in WNBA Finals, losing all three times to the Houston Comets. "We have got two in L.A. I feel better about our chances now of trying to complete this thing with two times to do it,'' Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. After trailing by as many as nine points in the first half, the Sparks didn't panic. Instead, Mabika, Leslie and Milton led a second-half surge. "I knew that we had been here before, down by 10 and 15 and came back,'' said Mabika, who scored 14 second-half points. "That's the thing about us and the playoffs. We tried to keep the game close in the first half and then take the lead in the second half.'' That's just what the Sparks did after going into the break tied at 35. They took a six-point lead with 11:48 to go and never faltered despite several Liberty attempts at a comeback. Los Angeles also shut down New York's inside game. Forward Tamika Whitmore, who averaged 12.7 points during the regular season, had just five points on 2-of-9 shooting. The Sparks outrebounded the Liberty 37-25. "Tamika Whitmore has always been a vital part of their offense,'' Leslie said. "She's probably the most versatile out of all the post players they have on the team. Tonight that was my job ... to really stymie her.'' The Sparks won without starting guard Tamecka Dixon, who injured her back and knee coming off the team bus for the morning shootaround. Cooper said it will be a gametime decision whether Dixon can play in Game 2. In Dixon's place, Latasha Byears scored six points and grabbed 11 rebounds. Guard Nikki Teasley set a record for assists in a finals game with 11. "With Dixon being unable to play, they went with their big lineup with Milton, Leslie and Byears,'' Liberty coach Richie Adubato said. "That big lineup caused us a lot of problems because we couldn't rebound as well as we would have.'' The Liberty faces a difficult challenge if they are going to win their first WNBA championship in four tries. Only one team has lost Game 1 of the finals and gone on to win the championship -- Houston in 1998. Reserve Becky Hammon led New York with 18 points, including four 3-pointers. The Liberty set a finals record with nine 3s in the game. The teams split in the regular season, and Game 1 of the finals was just as close. Los Angeles withstood several Liberty rallies in the second half, including one with less than two minutes to play. Sue Wicks hit a 3-pointer with 1:24 left to bring the Liberty to 64-61, but Milton scored on the next Sparks possession to seal it. "I don't know if I was necessarily the go-to person,'' Milton said. "I was just in a situation where the ball needed to go up.'' The teams traded baskets to start the second half, and the Sparks went on a 6-0 run to open a 49-43 lead with 11:48 remaining. They did not trail again. No matter how hard the Liberty tried to come back, the Sparks always had an answer. After the Liberty cut the lead to three with 8:53 to play, Mabika hit a 3-pointer. The Liberty cut it to 60-56, but Mabika answered with a field goal. Milton's basket with a minute to play put an end to the Liberty's final run. New York used seven 3-pointers to open a 31-22 lead with 6:16 remaining in the first half. But the Liberty scored just four points the rest of the half and the Sparks took advantage. "We feel good,'' Teasley said. "We are playing well at home and doing good in the playoffs. We are looking to take it on Saturday and get it over with.'' The Liberty shot 70 percent (7-of-10) from 3-point range in the first half.

Game notes
Among the crowd of 17,666 at Madison Square Garden were New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg, NBA commissioner David Stern, WNBA President Val Ackerman, Martina Navratilova, Rick Fox, Charlie Ward, Penny Marshall and Joan Jett.
